    {
      "question": "Show that for any positive integer $n$, $n^3 - n$ is divisible by $6$.",
      "answer": "$n^3 - n = (n-1)n(n+1)$, which is a product of three consecutive integers, hence divisible by $3! = 6$.",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Factorize the expression $n^3 - n$ as $n(n^2 - 1)$.",
          "Further factorize to get $n(n-1)(n+1)$.",
          "Identify that this is the product of three consecutive integers.",
          "State that in any set of three consecutive integers, at least one must be even and exactly one must be a multiple of three.",
          "Conclude that the product must be divisible by $2 \\times 3 = 6$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$n^3 - n = n(n^2 - 1) \\\\ = (n-1)n(n+1) \\\\ \\text{Since } (n-1), n, (n+1) \\text{ are three consecutive integers, their product is divisible by } 3! = 6.$"
      },
      "topic": "Real Numbers",
      "subtopic": "Euclid's Division Lemma",
      "marks": 4,
      "type": "la",
